The funny thing about the two of us is... 
 
We literally think we can do anything, as long as we’re in it together. No fear, no hesitation, our grit and determination. 
 
This includes cutting down an almost nineteen foot tree, tying it to our mini jeep, and getting it home and upright in our living room. 
 
Most of this process went off without a hitch, and we were all smiles driving this enormous tree home through the fresh snow. 
 
It’s when we got it in the house that we realized... maybe we bit off more then we could chew. 
 
Truth be told, I think we both secretly wanted to live out that Griswold family Christmas tree scenario we love so much. And we honestly came so close when we dropped it (twice), in the house, and almost broke through a window 🎄😂 
 
All that to say, I love the tree. I love the adventures we find ourselves in. And I love Matt. We needed that joy, more than we even knew. Here’s to a nineteen foot tree with three foot cut off the bottom in order to get it standing tall. 
 
Merry, merry everyone...

Twenty + One... 
 
Twenty one years of magic, adventure, love, fighting, poetry, dancing, laughing, cleaning, cooking, laundry, driving, chores, errands. Some meanness, lots of kindness, apologies. And mostly, at the heart of it... unconditional, never-ending, captivating, fiery, un-dying, for-ever true love... 
 
More years together than apart... my darling husband, there will never be enough years on this earth with you that will ever satisfy my heart. 
 
We married on a morning whim, New Years Eve, all on our own. Making our declarations and proclamations up on a desert hill in Tucson, Arizona. Getting ready for the adventure of a lifetime. I love sharing this holiday with our marital union. To get to spend the day reflecting and celebrating and making a plan for what's next. 
 
Cheers to love, hardship, strength, perseverance, and a beautiful, intentional, fun, adventures, and most of all... HAPPY New Year... 
 
🥂

Here's to another year of chasing the light... 
 
I'm not one to set many intentions on the first day of a new year. Unpopular opinion, I know. By the last week of the year I'm pretty tired, and by the first I'm just glad it's over. However, I do feel a genuine sense of optimism for the year ahead. Seemingly out of nowhere, things feel better for me. 
 
Without going too deep, and certainly without alarm bells or dramatics, twenty twenty-two was probably my... hmmmm... least favorite year. A life shift I was quite looking forward to turned into a living nightmare. More emotions to process than I was ready for. Just one of those life moments, bound for us all, that shoves you of the cliffs edge you didn't even know you were standing by. 
 
But you know what they say about the darkest hour... 
 
Chasing light gave me a sense of purpose and relief. I found what was bigger than myself. I found peace. joy. and hope. I will continue this practice. 
 
Happy New Year friends. Here's to shedding our leaves of twenty twenty-two so that we may create the canopy of our dreams in twenty twenty-three. Or 'twenty-four... no presh! 
 
☀️

Hi 2023 👋🏼  
  
The New Year really starts on a Monday I think, and I'm totally taking my time to tip-toe on in.  
  
I resumed my sunrise walk this morning after a nice long December break. It was freezing and full of snow and ice so, no thank you. I started a post walk pilates class, just today and just because it felt like a hell yes and is in no way a resolution of sorts. Then I accepted Matt’s kind offer to take the lead on re-opening the studio, which meant working in the cold while the heater fired back up and sweeping out the whole of December that we ignored on our way out last year. Gladly, I hung back and I ate second breakfast while sipping my coffee for a minute longer.  
  
Isn't it weird how we fully start to settle into our vacations just as they are ending? It's a crime really...  
  
Once I made my way over to my freshly cleaning little work station, with scissors and thread all lined up and ready for me, my excitement for the work came flooding back. We had a super productive day and if you’re waiting on your New Year’s bag, we’re working on it!! 
  
Hope everyone took this Monday at the exact pace that was best for them...  
 
👌🏼✌🏼🤟🏼

Yesterday was our son Noah's twenty first birthday. My goodness... twenty-one years.  
  
I spent the few days leading up to his birthday feeling a bit anxious. Mostly I think, because he's on the opposite side of the country at present. Starting his own life's journey. Alone. Not tucked safely by my side.  
  
The day of was spent fending off the tears. But slowly they came. While I flipped through old photos.  
  
Tears of joy that it all happened. Tears of sadness that it's all come to an end. Tears of regret for the moments I wish I could have done better. Tears of relief for the times I knew just what to do. Tears for the nerve-wracking years ahead as he makes his own way in the world, far from me. Tears filled with excited anticipation for what is yet to come for him ...  
  
All the emotions. All the gratitude. I have truly loved this chapter of my life. More than any of the rest. We were so full to the brim with love and excitement and adventure. We had plenty of hardship, growing pains, and turmoil as well.  
  
Despite everything and because of it all, we exist as one. Intertwined for infinity.  
  
I can't think of anything better then that.  
  
My kids stories are theirs to tell. I've spared them from a life of posing for photos they don't feel like taking, to share about them when maybe they don't feel like being shared.  
  
But my story is mine to tell and it's as simple as this... I would not have traded this life as their mom for anything. And my only wish is that I could go back and do it all again. I just loved it so much.  
  
Happy twenty-one years to us. We did it.

Today we did one of my favorite things, something I had completely forgotten about... and it wasn't eating a cheeseboard. Even though I love that too.     
     
I think our superpower, as two humans who have been through and managed quite a lot of life together, is our innate ability to make a solid list. Not just any list, but a list that defines the exact life we want to create and a path forward to attain it.     
     
We realized yesterday that we had not made a new list in quite some time. Like an alarmingly LONG time. Way too long of a time. So we took this morning and made three wildly-out-there, excitingly-expansive, brand-spanking-new, sparkly lists. They cover everything from the big gigantic future picture to the granular everyday practices we want to start RIGHT NOW.     
     
I can't believe that I forgot how life-giving the simple act of list making is. Just three small pages have elicited such clarity, hope, momentum, and joy. Having a blueprint for what comes next, tomorrow and ten years from now... is everything.     
     
I'm grateful for the best life, list-making partner. He always knows the perfect order to make the list in, how to craft just the right conveyances, and he has the best handwriting... which means I can just sit back with my coffee and dream up our perfect future scenario while he does all the harder, on-paper work :)   
   
Do you list make? Do you have a list making partner?    
    
Happy belated Valentine's Day... ❤️

I mean, you guys... This story is so crazy...  
  
Our son Noah was living out his young hero's journey, residing in a youth hostel in Mission Beach California, on a search to finding his true north. To finding himself. He bailed at the skatepark and his elbow popped clear out of its socket. 
 
For as bad as it looked, we all decided that it would be best if he come back home to Vermont for proper care from his family and doctors.  
  
With it popped back in place and in temp cast situation, he drove himself all the way home. Single-handedly. Literally.  
  
He arrived yesterday afternoon and within ten minutes we unwrapped his arm. Matt was like, that doesn't look right bro, and immediately brought him to the ER. 
 
He drove three thousand miles, alone, with his elbow out of socket. 😳  
  
We spent today in the surgical unit at the Middlebury hospital. They were able to put it back into place thank God, while he was under anesthesia. It is uncertain whether it will stay put or if he will need further surgery. 
 
We've come out of this today understanding a couple of things. First and foremost, Noah's pain threshold is second to none. Almost freakish really. Secondly, we are so blessed. We are lucky to have him home. We are lucky that his injury wasn't worse than it is. We are just so lucky to have each other. And there's nothing like seeing your kiddo wheeled away on a hospital bed to burn these things into your very soul. 
  
Hug your people. Life is fast and furious sometimes.
I feel like this was the perfect last performance. Well done Winter, well done…

I watch diligently out the window for deer, squirrel, and/or bear to ensure all blossoms remain intact, on tree, and not eaten. 
 
I've taken to giving them each a big drink of delicious, perfect, coherent water a day. 
 
I've never been very successful at growing any plants, especially outdoors, especially especially trees! 
 
The resilience they have shown over this harsh winter and the steadfast and vibrant nature in which they are returing... well, it feels like I'm witnessing a nothing short of a miracle. 
 
Here's to a beautiful weekend ahead, full of the everyday magic that is constantly surrounding us.

Good morning from the only person who didn't join threads yesterday... 😅😂  
  
The only good thing to come out of 30 million people doing a thing all at once was me being directed to the president of instagram's post, announcing this new app, only to be followed by a very long thread of comments screaming all the things I've been thinking, saying, and feeling for years. What a moment of validation that was... with my morning coffee. So nice.  
  
I've never thought that complaining about a platform while being on the platform was ever in very good taste. We all have a choice to be here, or not. But, like so many of you on here, who've used it to build a business, a livelihood... I am left scratching my head about why it went from being so awesome to literally the bane of my existence.  
  
I too miss the old days of insta. I personally prefer still photography over video and reels. I miss so much all of the authentic creativity. The quick snap of a morning coffee and scone. I really, really don't like the million awkward dances while people point at words and statements.  
  
I used to feel so much more connection here. It used to be worth it. Now it feels like a never-ending void of ads and videos and suggested posts that I am no way interested in and didn't ask to see.  
  
So, yea… this is the post that I said I'd never write. And for me, it's honestly a bigger conversation than just insta or new social media platforms. Like, where are we all heading? Are we really going to continue into this phone staring zombie world? Right off the proverbial zombie walk cliff? Into a meta verse? Like really? I'm just like a hard no on that. 
 
But how do we decouple ourselves, return to the old ways, reclaim our health, our hearts, our eyeballs, our sovereignty. Real life connection? These are my actual questions.   
  
I see none of my people here anymore. All the makers and travelers and local businesses that I loved to keep up with, all sucked into the vapid wasteland of the black hole we call algorithm, never to be seen again I guess...  
  
Hi 👋🏼 if you're out there. Be careful with your heart and your identity....

There's no looking back now... 
 
I used to run on pure adrenal come winter. Being a desert native, it made every single moment of fall and winter feel so incredibly magical. I wanted to ask everyone I met if they were seeing this magic too???  I was bursting at the seems with enthusiasm and joy.
 
Now, as a ten-plus year veteran, it takes a bit more than adrenaline for me to successfully make it through winter. And I'm only really just learning the proper techniques honestly. Spending many years sort of slogging it out, crawling on my hands and knees to the finish line. 
 
I read an article recently that asked the question, is Melatonin the new Vitamin D? Both master hormones. Both a requirement for a healthy balanced system. One more predominantly made in summer and the other in winter. I pay attention to these but I do not "take" either, I prefer to make my hormones naturally. 
 
So this year I have plans. To lean into the darkness and more so into the rest. To accept and surrender to the season of internal restorative repair. To further my disconnection from artificial light, especially in the morning and at night. To try and sneak my bare feet onto the cold earth each day, even if just for a second. To keep connected with the light outside. Sauna, cold therapy, warm baths, and lots of reading. 
 
Less food, less movement, more stretching, lots of breathing. 
 
Who new making it through a north country winter is actually like an Olympic sport, score based though on how little you did, and how much you allowed for rest and repair. No easy feat, rest is my hardest activity. 
 
So how are we feeling collectively? Anyone else have tactics for the Winter Olympics ahead? Asking for a a friend...
